block content 
    h1.bd-title#content Pagination
    p.bd-lead Documentation and examples for showing pagination to indicate a series of related content exists across multiple pages.
    
    h2#overview Overview
    p
        | We use a large block of connected links for our pagination, making links hard to miss and easily scalable—all while providing large hit areas. Pagination is built with list HTML elements so screen readers can announce the number of available links. Use a wrapping 
        code.highlighter-rouge &lt;nav&gt;
        |  element to identify it as a navigation section to screen readers and other assistive technologies.
    p
        | In addition, as pages likely have more than one such navigation section, it’s advisable to provide a descriptive 
        code.highlighter-rouge aria-label
        |  for the 
        code.highlighter-rouge &lt;nav&gt;
        |  to reflect its purpose. For example, if the pagination component is used to navigate between a set of search results, an appropriate label could be 
        code.highlighter-rouge aria-label="Search results pages"
        | .
    .bd-example
        +pagination([
            {text:'Previous',url:'#'},
            {text:'1',url:'#'},
            {text:'2',url:'#'},
            {text:'3',url:'#'},
            {text:'Next',url:'#'}
        ])

    figure.highlight
        pre
            code.js.
                +pagination([
                    {text:'Previous',url:'#'},
                    {text:'1',url:'#'},
                    {text:'2',url:'#'},
                    {text:'3',url:'#'},
                    {text:'Next',url:'#'}
                ])
    
    h2#working-with-icons Working with icons
    p
        | Looking to use an icon or symbol in place of text for some pagination links? Be sure to provide proper screen reader support with 
        code.highlighter-rouge aria
        |  attributes and the 
        code.highlighter-rouge .sr-only
        |  utility.
    .bd-example
        +pagination([
            {text:'Previous',url:'#',icon:'«'},
            {text:'1',url:'#'},
            {text:'2',url:'#'},
            {text:'3',url:'#'},
            {text:'Next',url:'#',icon:'»'}
        ])    
    figure.highlight
        pre
            code.js.
                +pagination([
                    {text:'Previous',url:'#',icon:'«'},
                    {text:'1',url:'#'},
                    {text:'2',url:'#'},
                    {text:'3',url:'#'},
                    {text:'Next',url:'#',icon:'»'}
                ])
    
    h2#disabled-and-active-states Disabled and active states
    p
        | Pagination links are customizable for different circumstances. Use 
        code.highlighter-rouge .disabled
        |  for links that appear un-clickable and 
        code.highlighter-rouge .active
        |  to indicate the current page.
    p
        | While the 
        code.highlighter-rouge .disabled
        |  class uses 
        code.highlighter-rouge pointer-events: none
        |  to 
        em try
        |  to disable the link functionality of 
        code.highlighter-rouge &lt;a&gt;
        | s, that CSS property is not yet standardized and doesn’t account for keyboard navigation. As such, you should always add 
        code.highlighter-rouge tabindex="-1"
        |  on disabled links and use custom JavaScript to fully disable their functionality.
    .bd-example
        +pagination([
            {text:'Previous',url:'#',style:'disabled'},
            {text:'1',url:'#'},
            {text:'2',url:'#',style:'active'},
            {text:'3',url:'#'},
            {text:'Next',url:'#'}
        ])
    figure.highlight
        pre
